    "output": {
      "text": "**Econ** is a common shorthand for **economics**, the social science that studies how societies allocate scarce resources to satisfy unlimited wants and needs. It examines:\n\n| Aspect | What it looks at |\n|--------|------------------|\n| **Production** | How goods and services are created (factors of production, technology, firms). |\n| **Distribution** | Who gets the output (income, wealth, market mechanisms). |\n| **Consumption** | How individuals and groups use goods and services. |\n| **Markets & Prices** | How supply and demand interact to set prices and allocate resources. |\n| **Policy** | Government actions (taxes, subsidies, regulations) that influence economic outcomes. |\n| **Macro vs. Micro** | *Microeconomics* focuses on individual agents (households, firms); *macroeconomics* looks at aggregate variables (GDP, inflation, unemployment). |\n\nIn everyday usage, “econ” can also refer to:\n\n- **Econ classes** – college courses on economics.\n- **Econ majors** – students pursuing a degree in economics.\n- **Econ data** – economic statistics like GDP, CPI, or employment figures.\n\nSo, when someone mentions “econ,” they’re usually talking about the study of how people and societies make choices about producing, distributing, and consuming limited resources.",
